{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/how-to-get-data-on-every-nba-player-using-r-62abcacd65e1", "time": 1683006164.9777641, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/how-to-get-data-on-every-nba-player-using-r-62abcacd65e1/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "How to Get Data on Every NBA Player Using R | by Josh Gonzales, PhD(c) | Towards Data Science", "h1": "How to Get Data on Every NBA Player Using R", "description": "The NBA season is on hold. Which, you could look at as a negative and just watch \u201cThe Last Dance\u201d on repeat. Or, you could look at this as an opportunity to finally learn how to do some data science\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://medium.com/r-tutorials/r-functions-daily-read-csv-3c418c25cba4", "anchor_text": "load a tibble", "paragraph_index": 5}], "all_paragraphs": ["The NBA season is on hold. Which, you could look at as a negative and just watch \u201cThe Last Dance\u201d on repeat.", "Or, you could look at this as an opportunity to finally learn how to do some data science on the NBA and really learn the history of the league and the players.", "There are a few R packages that that let you grab NBA data. I use the one called nbastatR because it\u2019s the one with the best implementation in my opinion. To install the package, use the following command:", "Then all you need to do to load the package is use:", "There are a lot of functions within nbastatR, but let\u2019s first get a matrix of every NBA player using:", "This will load a tibble called \u201cdf_dict_nba_players\u201d with every NBA player. Ever.", "Each observation is a player, and there are 17 variables for each player. The ones that are immediately relevant are:", "You can explore the other variables at your leisure. The important part is that you now know the id number of every player. While many of the functions in nbastatR can still work if you use player names, some NBA players have similar names, and typos are easily made. If you use a player\u2019s id you will never have these problems.", "Let\u2019s do a quick example of getting LeBron James\u2019 data using nbastatR\u2019s \u201cplayers_career\u201d function.", "The players_career function requires only one input at minimum:", "You can call this function in R using", "Note: you could have used players_careers(players = \u201cLeBron James\u201d) instead but I keep it as a list in case I want find data on more than one player.", "Calling this function will return 8 tables:", "There\u2019s a lot of data within each of these tibbles. You should explore what each gives you to get a better sense of nbastatR\u2019s capabilities.", "Alternatively, you could have invoked LeBron\u2019s player id instead of his name using:", "This will give you the exact same result, but I prefer using the player_ids method because I know that it won\u2019t give me mistakes on other players less famous than LeBron.", "You can also add in another input called \u201cmode\u201d and load data onto a variable if you want something more specific.", "For example, to get LeBron\u2019s career totals you can use:", "You now have a tibble that looks like this:", "The nameTable variable tells you exactly what data is being stored in each dataTable variable. If you click on a dataTable variable, it\u2019ll open up another table with more data.", "For example, clicking on the dataTable for SeasonTotalsRegularSeason gives you a table that has all of LeBron\u2019s regular season totals in each of the seasons he\u2019s played in the NBA. (it\u2019s two screenshots because I couldn\u2019t fit all the variables on one screen):", "The mode input requires one of the following designations:", "So if you\u2019re more interested in a player\u2019s per game or per 36 minute numbers, use one of the other modes instead. You could also call all three modes using:", "This will give you a \u201ctable of tables\u201d with all three modes applied.", "This is just the tip of the iceberg. There are so many other functions in nbastatR. This was just a basic way of getting player data using R.", "There is a lot of data to explore, so have fun with it! If you have a specific question you\u2019d like me answer in a future post, don\u2019t be afraid to let me know in the comments below.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "PhD Candidate @ University of Guelph. I study nostalgia and representation in marketing and consumer behaviour."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F62abcacd65e1&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fhow-to-get-data-on-every-nba-player-using-r-62abcacd65e1&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fhow-to-get-data-on-every-nba-player-using-r-62abcacd65e1&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fnew-story&source=---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------new_post_sidenav-----------", "anchor_text": "Write"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/search?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fhow-to-get-data-on-every-nba-player-using-r-62abcacd65e1&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "an